*************************** Microservices-Based E-Commerce System ***********************************

Project Summary

This is a personal project where I designed and built an e-commerce system using a microservices approach. The focus of this project was not UI or visual design, 
but understanding how real production systems are structured, how services communicate with each other, and how scalability and deployment are planned in real companies.
The system is split into independent services, each with its own responsibility, database, and APIs. Even though the project is not deployed to production, 
it is designed in a way that can be deployed using containerization and orchestration tools.

Overall Architecture
The application is built using four independent microservices, each handling a specific part of the e-commerce flow. 
Services communicate using REST APIs for synchronous operations and Kafka events for asynchronous communication.

Each service:
	• Has its own codebase
	• Has its own database
	• Can be scaled independently
	• Is containerized using Docker
A small React application is used only to test service integration and payment flows.

Microservices Breakdown
*************** 1. Catalog Service ***************
Responsibility
	• Manages product data and inventory
	• Exposes REST APIs for product-related operations
Key Work
	• Product schema and database design
	• CRUD APIs for products
	• Handles stock updates based on events from the Order service
	• Independent datastore to avoid tight coupling with other services

***************** 2. Order Service *******************
Responsibility
	• Manages cart (quote) creation and line items
	• Handles order submission and order lifecycle
Key Work
	• Cart creation and update APIs
	• Order placement logic
	• Publishes Kafka events when an order is placed
	• Consumes payment status events from the Payment service
	• Updates order status based on payment results
	• Coordinates with Catalog service to update stock through events
This service acts as the core business workflow of the system.

****************** 3. Payment Service ************************
Responsibility
	• Handles payment processing
	• Notifies other services about payment status
Key Work
	• Integrated Stripe in a loosely coupled way
	• Processes payment requests
	• Publishes Kafka events on payment success or failure
	• Does not directly depend on Order or Catalog service logic
This design allows payment providers to be changed with minimal impact.

********************* 4. User Authentication Service ***************************
Responsibility
	• Manages user authentication and authorization
	• Controls access to protected APIs
Key Work
	• User login and token generation
	• JWT-based authentication
	• Token validation for secured service calls
	• Acts as a middleware layer for protected routes

Data Management
	• Each service has its own database based on its use case
	• Used ORMs like Prisma and Drizzle
	• Database schemas are versioned using migrations
	• Single-command setup for database initialization and updates
This avoids shared databases and keeps services independent.

Communication & Security
	• REST APIs for direct service calls
	• Kafka for event-based communication
	• JWT tokens for secure API access
	• CORS configuration for cross-origin requests
	• Services remain loosely coupled through events instead of direct dependencies

********************** Tech Stack **************************
	• Backend: Node.js, TypeScript
	• Architecture: Microservices
	• Messaging: Kafka
	• Database: PostgreSQL / other service-specific stores
	• ORMs: Prisma, Drizzle
	• Search & throughput: Elasticsearch
	• Authentication: JWT
	• Frontend (for testing): React
	• Containerization: Docker, Docker Compose

Code Structure & Design Approach
	• Clear separation of controller, service, and data layers
	• Mix of class-based and functional patterns where appropriate
	• Loosely coupled service layers
	• Basic understanding of SOLID principles applied in service design
	• Focus on readability and maintainability

Deployment & Cloud Design (Planned Architecture)
Although this project is not deployed, it is designed with a real deployment flow in mind.
Container & CI/CD Flow
	• Each service has its own Dockerfile
	• All services can run locally using Docker Compose
	• GitHub repository can be used to trigger build and test pipelines on push
	• Unit tests and build checks before deployment

Kubernetes & Scaling Plan
	• Each microservice can be deployed as a separate Kubernetes deployment
	• Horizontal scaling based on traffic
	• Independent scaling for high-traffic services like Order and Catalog
	• Health checks and rolling updates

AWS Infrastructure Plan
	• EC2 instances for running Kubernetes workloads
	• Nginx as reverse proxy and API gateway
	• Load balancer to distribute traffic across services
	• AWS Secrets Manager for managing environment variables and sensitive configs
	• Configuration handled through YAML files and environment variables
	• Route53 to expose public URLs

Challenges Faced
	• Managing large configuration files across multiple services
	• Setting up Kafka producers and consumers correctly
	• Keeping service boundaries clean
	• Handling async workflows like order → payment → status update
	• Coordinating database migrations across services

What This Project Shows
	• Understanding of microservices architecture
	• Experience with event-driven communication
	• Knowledge of containerization and orchestration concepts
	• Practical understanding of cloud deployment planning
	• Ability to design systems that can scale
	• Ownership of end-to-end backend design

Why This Project Is Important
This project reflects how modern backend systems are built in real companies. It shows that I understand not only how to write APIs, 
but also how services interact, how systems scale, and how deployments are planned in production environments.


